<div id="review_4110512449" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4110512449" />
    <a title="Mark Porton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18643650-mark-porton"><img alt="Mark Porton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1591876752p2/18643650.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4110512449?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark Porton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark Porton" href="/user/show/18643650-mark-porton">Mark Porton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark-porton?shelf=history">history</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark-porton?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark-porton?shelf=funny">funny</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark-porton?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/18643650-mark-porton?shelf=shakespeare">shakespeare</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4110512449" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4981556748827716188">“<i>Don’t rattle on about my favourite character, don’t rattle on about my favourite character, don’t rattle on about my favourite character, don’t rattle on about my favourite character.</i>” <br/><br/>Okay. Note to self: <i>Don’t mention him Mark!!</i>.<br/><br/>Having said that – Sir John Falstaff elevated himself to even greater heights of absurdity and descending to deeper depths of skulduggery, in <b>Henry IV, part 2 – by William Shakespeare</b> compared to his dodgy dealings in Henry IV part 1. Unbelievable, but he did.<br/><br/>Okay, bac</span>
  <span id="freeText4981556748827716188" style="display:none">“<i>Don’t rattle on about my favourite character, don’t rattle on about my favourite character, don’t rattle on about my favourite character, don’t rattle on about my favourite character.</i>” <br /><br />Okay. Note to self: <i>Don’t mention him Mark!!</i>.<br /><br />Having said that – Sir John Falstaff elevated himself to even greater heights of absurdity and descending to deeper depths of skulduggery, in <b>Henry IV, part 2 – by William Shakespeare</b> compared to his dodgy dealings in Henry IV part 1. Unbelievable, but he did.<br /><br />Okay, back to Falstaff - He was at his brilliant best, on top of his game – one moment I found myself cringing at his conniving, lying, cheating and general dirty deeds. The next moment I found myself laughing (out loud) at some ridiculous scene involving something like a ridiculous slap stick fight, where the minds-eye visuals were hilarious then all of a sudden I felt dreadfully sorry for him due to the predicament he found himself in, all due to his self-inflicted misdemeanours. How can one character engender such opposite emotions. This guy is so well written, he’s also wonderfully acted in the BBC’s The Hollow Crown. Yep – I watched that brilliant production concurrently with the play and the study notes. This is proving to be a worthwhile modus operandi for me to really enjoy <i>The Bard’s</i> plays, and it’s working!!<br /><br />This play is my favourite so far, by far. A great mix of political intrigue and farcical hilarity. We are introduced to new characters of course, my favourites being the hopelessly sycophantic, lightweight, and quite silly Justices, Shallow and Silence. Then there’s the stuffy but immensely capable old Chief Justice who, quite rightly takes an extreme dislike on Falstaff. <br /><br />I particularly remembered the dishonourable actions of Prince John when dealing with the rebels, how he went against his word with catastrophic consequences for the said rebels, and then was weaselly enough to try and explain “on a technicality” why he didn’t keep his word. I had liked him up until that point. That bothered me.<br /><br />Dolly Tearsheet, Falstaff’s ‘go-to’ prostitute is a potty mouthed, rough woman – qualities she has obviously needed to survive in the squalor of Eastcheap. Mistress Quickly, who runs the Boar’s Head Tavern in Eastcheap is a sociable, friendly enough old woman – she would have her hands full running the Boar’s Head that’s for sure.<br /><br />It also bothered me that Prince Hal (Harry, or the future King Henry V) changed so drastically once his father died (c. 1413) when he was crowned King. Even though this change was expected from various scenes in Henry IV, part 1 – I didn’t think he’d be so callous to do it in such a way as he did. It was appalling. <br /><br />That’s enough from me on this one, I loved it. Now bring on Henry V and I hope he lifts his game as in real-life history he was a decent King. He invaded France a couple of times including the legendary Battle of Agincourt. This Warrior King spent a great deal of his time at war – I would expect this will be covered in Shakespeare’s next instalment, fun times ahead.<br /><br />Well played Sir John Falstaff, Sir!<br /><br /><b>5-stars</b><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4981556748827716188" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


